---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const nav = [
  { label: 'Overview', href: '#overview' },
  { label: 'Process', href: '#process' },
  { label: 'Final Solution', href: '#solution' },
  { label: 'Reflection', href: '#reflection' },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Design Challenge"
  heading="Design large data tables"
  role="Designer"
  team="Solo Project"
  timeline="8 hours"
  projectType="Product Design"
  nav={nav}
>
  <section id="overview">
    <h3>Context</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      This table is used by school principals to view and assess teacher applicants. It currently
      supports grouping, filtering, and tags.
    </p>
    <h3>Problem</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      How might we give users more context through the applicant table while considering usability
      and scalability?
    </p>
    <h3>new requirements</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Applicant Review</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Show application review status, when and who has reviewed the application. Bonus: Show 3
          reviewers inline
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Pagination</h2>
        <p class="lead">Show 20 rows per page.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Ratings</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Add a 5-point rating system per applicant, allow for multiple ratings. This should be
          editable from the table.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Other Flags</h2>
        <p class="lead">Support up to 3 other flags per row.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">
      Considerations: developer-friendly naming conventions, WCAG AA compliance, file cleanliness,
      hand-off documentation, device responsiveness.
    </p>
    <h3>My solution</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Key information on the table view with a side panel for details about the applicant.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="process">
    <h3>process</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I cycled between researching examples of existing products and iterating on my ideas.
    </p>
    <h3>pagination</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I redesigned pagination for greater control, adding page number input and arrow icons to
      navigation buttons.
    </p>
    <h3>overflow</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      After designing the new required columns, I put them onto the table to see what it would look
      like.
    </p>
    <h3>inital problem statement</h3>
    <p class="lead">How might we fit the new requirements onto the data table?</p>
    <h3>horizontal scroll</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      After researching products like notion and google sheets, I tried to implement a horizontal
      scroll design. Although this solution fits a theoretically infinite number of columns on the
      table, it hides information behind the fold and could add development difficulty.
    </p>
    <h3>Key Insight</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Initially, I assumed users needed to see all requirements within the table view. After
      researching examples and best practices, I realized the table's main purpose is to support
      comparison across candidates, not to display every applicant detail. This insight helped me
      reframe my problem statement with a user-centered focus.
    </p>
    <h3>new problem statement</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      How might we provide users with the context necessary at the right stage in the process of
      viewing an application?
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="solution">
    <h3>final solution</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Key columns are in the table view. To view the details, users can click each row to get more
      information about the user. If more information needs to be added, the side panel could become
      scrollable.
    </p>
    <h3>mobile responsiveness</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Key columns will be kept on the table with a panel that expands from the bottom of the screen.
    </p>
    <h3>handoff documentation</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I created a design system change log that outlines changes or new components. I used Dev-mode
      to annotate measurements.
    </p>
    <p>
      Next steps for the design system: introduce variables to make design responsive to mobile;
      some of the "new" components might already exist in the design system however I was not given
      the full system for this challenge.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="reflection">
    <h3>takeaways</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Keep Researching</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Don't assume your first solution is the only way to approach something, look at what other
          designers have done and how it works on live products.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Collaborate</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Consider how you can involve the client or developer or user at different points of the
          process to make sure your design is thoughtful and feasible.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Be Comfortable with Ambiguity</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Since this was a challenge, the details of the project were open ended. It's important to
          ask for clarification when necessary and take advantage of ambiguity to think outside the
          box!
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="!mt-12">next steps</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>UX Research</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Conduct user testing to gather insights and affirm or reject concept
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Identify Constraints</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Discuss with client/product manager and development team to identify budget/time
          constraints
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Consider Edge Cases</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          What happens when the user wants to add a column? Is the side panel editable? Do users
          want to compare data while they see the details?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>
</CaseStudyLayout>
